State MSM Profile: Kentucky

Background & Methods

In 2015-2016, researchers at Emory University partnered with colleagues at the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) to develop methods to estimate the number of men who have sex with men (MSM) residing in each county in the United States. Using population and housing data from the American Community Survey and estimates from two peer-reviewed publications (Oster et al., 2015 & Purcell et al., 2012), they derived an indirect estimate of MSM population sizes that took into account both the urbanicity of the county as well as its density of households with a male householder and a male same-sex partner.

The full methodology is published in the Journal of Medical Internet Research - Public Health and Surveillance:

Grey JA, Bernstein KT, Sullivan PS, Purcell DW, Chesson HW, Gift TL, Rosenberg ES. Estimating the population sizes of men who have sex with men in US states and counties using data from the American Community Survey. JMIR Public Health Surveill 2016;2(1):e14. DOI: 10.2196/publichealth.5365

Overview of MSM in Kentucky

An estimated 47,034 men who have sex with men (MSM) resided in Kentucky in 2013, representing 1.0% of the 4,503,084 MSM in the United States. Of the 1,621,844 adult men of Kentucky, 2.9% had had sex with another man in the past 5 years, which was less than the overall percentage of adult men in the United States who were MSM (3.9%).

Most MSM in Kentucky resided in central counties of large metropolitan areas (35.5%). Including both central and fringe counties, 55.1% resided in a large metropolitan area.


Percentage of MSM by urbanicity, United States and Kentucky, 2013

MSM in Kentucky Counties

Among counties or county-equivalent areas in Kentucky, Jefferson County had the largest population of MSM at 16,681, representing 35.5% of all MSM in the state. Jefferson County also had the highest percentage of MSM among adult men in Kentucky at 6.1%. This was greater than the percentage for Kentucky as a whole, which was 2.9% of adult men.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.



MSM in Kentucky Metropolitan Statistical Areas

Louisville/Jefferson County Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Louisville/Jefferson County MSA overlaps two states: Indiana and Kentucky. The Kentucky portion of the MSA had the largest metropolitan population of MSM in Kentucky at 19,854, or 42.2% of all MSM in the state and 84.3% of the 23,549 MSM in the MSA. Of the 354,493 adult men in the Kentucky part of Louisville/Jefferson County, an estimated 5.6% were MSM. This was greater than the percentage of MSM among adult men in the MSA as a whole, which was 5.1% of adult men (23,549 out of 457,349).



Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.




Cincinnati Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Cincinnati MSA overlaps three states: Indiana, Kentucky and Ohio. The Kentucky portion of the MSA had 6,045 MSM, or 12.9% of all MSM in the state and 19.0% of the 31,781 MSM in the MSA. Of 155,754 adult men in the Kentucky part of Cincinnati, 3.9% were MSM. This was less than the overall percentage of MSM among adult men in the MSA, which was 4.1% of adult men (31,781 out of 770,623).

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.




Lexington-Fayette Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Lexington-Fayette MSA had a population of 4,730 MSM, or 10.1% of all MSM in Kentucky. Of the 179,752 adult men in Lexington-Fayette, an estimated 2.6% were MSM.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.




Owensboro Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Owensboro MSA had a population of 1,021 MSM, or 2.2% of all MSM in Kentucky. Of the 41,796 adult men in Owensboro, an estimated 2.4% were MSM.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.




Elizabethtown-Fort Knox Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Elizabethtown-Fort Knox MSA had a population of 912 MSM, or 1.9% of all MSM in Kentucky. Of the 54,691 adult men in Elizabethtown-Fort Knox, an estimated 1.7% were MSM.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.




Bowling Green Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Bowling Green MSA had a population of 860 MSM, or 1.8% of all MSM in Kentucky. Of the 60,046 adult men in Bowling Green, an estimated 1.4% were MSM.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.




Huntington-Ashland Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Huntington-Ashland MSA overlaps three states: Kentucky, Ohio and West Virginia. The Kentucky portion of the MSA had 682 MSM, or 1.5% of all MSM in the state and 26.5% of the 2,571 MSM in the MSA. Of 32,725 adult men in the Kentucky part of Huntington-Ashland, 2.1% were MSM. This was greater than the overall percentage of MSM among adult men in the MSA, which was 1.9% of adult men (2,571 out of 137,392).

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.




Evansville Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Evansville MSA overlaps two states: Indiana and Kentucky. The Kentucky portion of the MSA had 427 MSM, or 0.9% of all MSM in the state and 21.3% of the 2,005 MSM in the MSA. Of 16,784 adult men in the Kentucky part of Evansville, 2.5% were MSM. This was greater than the overall percentage of MSM among adult men in the MSA, which was 1.7% of adult men (2,005 out of 114,891).

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.




Clarksville Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Clarksville MSA overlaps two states: Kentucky and Tennessee. The Kentucky portion of the MSA had 422 MSM, or 0.9% of all MSM in the state and 35.3% of the 1,196 MSM in the MSA. Of 32,801 adult men in the Kentucky part of Clarksville, 1.3% were MSM. This was equal to the overall percentage of MSM among adult men in the MSA, which was 1.3% of adult men (1,196 out of 95,547).

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.
